          <li><strong>Gas spring lift</strong> — smooth adjustment from 4.5" to 19.7" with one hand</li>
          <li><strong>One-handed height adjustment</strong> — no cranking, holds at any height</li>
          <li><strong>Removable keyboard tray</strong> — separate level for ergonomic typing</li>
          <li><strong>No assembly required</strong> — ready in 5 minutes, folds flat for storage</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=standing+desk+converter&tag=toolwise20-20" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Check Current Price on Amazon</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: VIVO Black Height Adjustable Stand</h2>
      <p>The VIVO Height Adjustable Stand costs around $120 and uses a similar gas spring mechanism to the FlexiSpot, but with a narrower 23-inch surface and a slightly lower weight capacity of 33 pounds. It handles a single 27-inch monitor or a 24-inch monitor plus a laptop comfortably, but dual large monitors is a stretch.</p>
      <p>The main trade-off is assembly. The VIVO arrives in pieces and takes about 30 minutes to build with the included Allen wrench. The gas spring is also slightly stiffer, requiring a firmer push to lower. For a single-monitor setup where saving $50 matters, the VIVO is a capable alternative. If you run dual monitors or hate assembly, the FlexiSpot is worth the extra cost.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>Measure your desk depth before buying anything. A standing desk converter needs roughly 20 inches of depth when raised, and the keyboard tray extends another 10 inches in front. If your desk is shallower than 24 inches, the converter will overhang the front edge and feel unstable. Also weigh your monitors — a dual 27-inch setup can hit 30 pounds before you add a laptop, which rules out the cheapest converters rated for 25 pounds.</p>
      <p>The lift mechanism is the most important spec. Gas spring lifts are smooth, hold at any height, and require minimal force. Scissor-lift mechanisms (the zigzag metal arms) are cheaper but only lock at set heights and require more force. Avoid electric converters at this price range — the motors are weak and fail more often than gas springs.</p>
      <p>Common mistakes to avoid: do not buy a converter without a separate keyboard tray. If the keyboard sits on the same surface as the monitor, your wrists end up too high when standing. Do not overload the converter beyond its rated weight — the gas spring will fail to lift. And skip converters under $80; based on user reports they wobble enough at full height to make typing unpleasant.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Is a standing desk converter as good as a full standing desk?</summary>
          <p>For most users, yes. A converter gives you the sit-stand alternation that delivers the health benefits, without the cost or commitment of replacing your desk. The trade-off is reduced desk surface area and a slightly higher standing keyboard position, which most people adapt to within a week. Full standing desks win on surface area, but converters win on price and zero-install convenience.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How much weight can a standing desk converter hold?</summary>
          <p>Most quality converters hold 35 to 50 pounds, enough for two monitors and a laptop. The FlexiSpot is rated for 35 pounds and is designed to handle a 27-inch monitor, a 24-inch monitor, and a laptop without straining the gas spring. Always check the weight rating against your actual monitor weights before buying.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Do standing desk converters wobble?</summary>
          <p>Some wobble is normal at full height, but a well-built converter keeps it minimal. The FlexiSpot uses a gas spring with a wide X-frame base that is designed to remain stable even at the maximum 19.7-inch height. Cheaper scissor-lift designs wobble noticeably more and can make precise mouse work frustrating at standing height.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

